nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is rarely wrong to ruff a winning trick by declarer, particularly if you are not sure it will be overruffed. And, conversely, lisa should not ruff the 2nd low spade. Because it is not usually right to ruff a loser, unless you are ruffing high to try and set up a trump trick for partner. So, to summarize the two rules about ruffing.  It is usually right to ruff declarer's winners, even if you think they might be overruffed. At worst you are trading tricks. And it is usually not right to ruff declarer's loser  unless you intend to ruff high, to force out a high trump from declarer, and set up a trump winner for partner.|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|BTW, ruffing high to set up a trump trick for partner is known as a "trump promotion." To discuss a trump promotion slightly more, let me give you an example. Suppose they are in a 9 card fit, and you have Jx of trumps. If you ruff with the J, and partner started with Qx, you set up a trump trick  because if declarer overruffs with the A or K, partner's Q becomes good. If you ruff low, note that declarer can draw trumps in 2 rounds and not lose any trump tricks. So, that is an example of a trump promotion. Doesn't apply on this hand, but does come up quite a bit.|
