^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This was quite an interesting hand, for several reasons. First let us discuss lisa's one diamond opener. Many people advocate opening 1@D with 4 diamonds and 5 clubs and a minimum opening hand. The idea is that you can then rebid 2@C, which is not a reverse. If you open 1@C, you cannot bid 2@D as that is a reverse. However, I disagree with that style personally. As most of you know, I am a big believer in the law of total tricks, where knowing the combined number of cards you have in your suit is very important. So, if you open 1@D with lisa's hand, you never know whether lisa has 5 diamonds and 4 clubs, or 4 diamonds and 5 clubs. Thus, the problem for dee in whether to pass or bid 5@D.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people say that if lisa bids 2@C, that should show six, but I am not one of those people. I think it is ok to rebid clubs with 5 clubs. For example, if you are 2-4-2-5, and you open 1@C and partner bids 1@S, you  have to bid 2@C with your 5 card club suit (assuming you are not strong enough to reverse.) Therefore, I don't see any difference between a hand with 4 hearts and 5 clubs and a hand with 4 diamonds and 5 clubs. But, as I said, that is just my opinion. many people would open lisa's hand 1@D. To repeat, I do feel it is important to get your distribution across as accurately as possible. Now, as to the play.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First let me discuss my play to the first two tricks. I can see that we have 2 tricks for sure, a club and a heart and the whole hand is going to come down to the spade suit. So, I tried to make it as easy as possible for partner to not misdefend by accident. If I let partner win the first heart, he may lead a spade and blow up the hand  because a spade is a good return at trick 2, given the auction.  So, I overtook, and played the clubs to make sure that lisa had to figure out the spades herself.  On the other hand, continuing hearts gives lisa a ruff and sluff, so she also makes the hand that way, since she sluffs her losing spade from her hand.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to how lisa should play the spades. In this situation,  most experts would get the spade suit right. Let me explain why. After playing diamonds, clubs, and spades, lisa knows that South had 6 Hearts (from the preempt), 2 clubs, and 3 diamonds. Therefore, south started with 2 spades. South then started with 2-6-3-2 and I should have four Soades and it is twice as likely I have the @SQ. Then, percentage wise, lisa should play me for the Q. Counting out defender's hands seems hard to less experienced players, but if you practice for a while, it becomes easier as time goes on. I have a tutorial on counting out the hand on my web site. ^*Hwww.bridgesights.com/hondobridge/CountingDistribution.txt^*N  It is really a good skill to develop, and not as hard as many people think.|
