^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his important @E@3instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls"  which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you can find many more.

|FP|2|cp|8|at|
^C@2** |FP||cp||at|It is usually right to ruff declarer's winners, even if you think they might be overruffed. At worst you are trading tricks. And it is usually not right to ruff declarer's loser  unless you intend to ruff high, to force out a high trump from declarer, and set up a trump winner for partner.

|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|In "Trump Promotion", if they are in a 9 card fit, and you have Jx of trumps. If you ruff with the J, and partner started with Qx, you set up a trump trick  because if declarer overruffs with the A or K, partner's Q becomes good. If you ruff low, note that declarer can draw trumps in 2 rounds and not lose any trump tricks. 
|FP|2|cp|8|at| 
** |FP||cp||at|Once partner chooses a defense, it is usually a good idea to stick with it, unless it is obviously wrong.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|It is rarely right to pass a takeout double at the one level.  You should never pass because you have nothing to bid.    
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|On opening lead, your first obligation is to give attitude, but when it is obvious you don't like the suit, you should give count.  
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|It is always good tactics to lay claim to the spade suit when you can, as to outbid you, the opps have to go one level higher.   

